\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Credits: 3p.

\emph default
 On 
\series bold
\color blue
Paper
\series default
\color inherit
, show that the posterior for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Inverse-Gamma}(\alpha+n,\beta+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{k})$
\end_inset

.
\series bold
\color blue

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Solution
\series default
\color inherit
: From the table of distributions we get the prior density function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(\lambda)=\frac{\beta^{\alpha}}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\lambda^{-(\alpha+1)}\text{exp}(-\beta/\lambda).
\]

\end_inset

and the likelihood function is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(x|k,\lambda\right)=\prod_{i=1}^{n}p(x_{i}|k,\lambda)=\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{k}{\lambda}x_{i}^{k-1}\exp\left(-x_{i}^{k}/\lambda\right).
\]

\end_inset

Bayes' theorem gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(\lambda|x) & \propto p(x|k,\lambda)p(\lambda)\\
 & \propto\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{\lambda}\exp\left(-x_{i}^{k}/\lambda\right)\cdot\lambda^{-(\alpha+1)}\text{exp}(-\beta/\lambda)\\
 & \propto\lambda^{-(\alpha+n+1)}\text{exp}\left(-\frac{1}{\lambda}\left[\beta+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{k}\right]\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be identified as the form of an Inverse-Gamma distribution.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda|x\sim\text{Inverse-Gamma}(\alpha+n,\beta+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{k})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

